revision.text:
'''Cel''' was the [[Etruscan religion|Etruscan goddess]] of the [[earth]]. On the Etruscan calendar, the month of ''Celi'' (September) is likely named for her.<ref>Nancy Thomson De Grummond, ''Etruscan Myth, Sacred History, and Legend'' (University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, 2006), p. 43, 106.</ref> Her [[Interpretatio graeca|Greek counterpart]] is [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]] and her [[List of Roman deities|Roman]] is [[Terra (goddess)|Tellus]].
In [[Etruscan mythology]], Cel was the mother of the [[Gigantes|Giants]]. A [[bronze mirror]] from the 5th century BC depicts a [[theomachy]] in which '''Celsclan''', "son of Cel," is a Giant attacked by [[Laran]], the god of war. In Greek, "giant" comes from a word meaning "born from Gaia".<ref>De Grummond, ''Etruscan Myth'', p. 105.</ref> Another mirror depicts [[anguiped]] Giants in the company of a goddess, possibly Cel, whose lower body is formed of [[vegetation]].<ref>De Grummond, ''Etruscan Myth'', p. 105–106.</ref>
In a sanctuary near [[Lake Trasimeno]] were found five [[votive]] bronze statuettes, some male and some female, dedicated to her as ''Cel Ati'', "Mother Cel". The inscription on each reads ''mi celś atial celthi,'' "I [belong to, have been given] to Cel the mother, here [in this sanctuary]."<ref>Giuliano Bonfante and [[Larissa Bonfante]], ''The Etruscan Language: An Introduction'' (New York University Press, 2002, revised edition), p. 166.</ref>
Cel appears on the [[Liver of Piacenza]], a bronze model of a liver marked for the Etruscan practice of [[haruspicy]]. She is placed in House 13.{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}
