{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}
[[File:Jain Vegetarianism Illustration.jpg|thumb|The food choices of Jains are based on the value of Ahimsa (non-violence), and this makes the Jains to prefer food that inflict the least amount of violence]]
{{Jainism}}
{{Indian cuisine}}
'''Jain vegetarianism''' is practiced by the followers of [[Jainism|Jain]] culture and philosophy. It is one of the most rigorous forms of spiritually motivated diet on the Indian subcontinent and beyond. The Jain cuisine is completely [[vegetarianism|vegetarian]] and also excludes underground vegetables such as onion, garlic, etc, to prevent injuring small insects and microorganisms; and also to prevent the entire plant getting uprooted and killed. It is practised by Jain ascetics and lay Jains.<ref>{{cite web
|url=https://thoughtsfromajoy.wordpress.com/2012/01/25/vegetarian-garam-masala-recipe/
|title=An eggplant (aubergine) dish that’s fit for a king!
}}</ref>{{sfn|Natubhai Shah|2004|p=249}}

Jain objections to the eating of meat, fish and eggs are based on the principle of [[non-violence]] ([[Ahimsa in Jainism|ahimsa]], figuratively "non-injuring"). Every act by which a person directly or indirectly supports killing or injury is seen as act of violence (''himsa''), which creates harmful reaction [[karma]]. The aim of ahimsa is to prevent the accumulation of such karma.{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=26-30}}{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=191-195}} The extent to which this intention is put into effect varies greatly among Hindus, Buddhists and Jains. Jains believe nonviolence is the most essential religious duty for everyone (''ahinsā paramo dharmaḥ'', a statement often inscribed on Jain temples).{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=160}}{{sfn|Wiley|2006|p=438}}{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=153-154}} It is an indispensable condition for liberation from the cycle of [[reincarnation]],<ref>[[Hemacandra]], ''Yogashastra'' 2.31.</ref> which is the ultimate goal of all Jain activities. Jains share this goal with Hindus and Buddhists, but their approach is particularly rigorous and comprehensive. Their scrupulous and thorough way of applying nonviolence to everyday activities, and especially to food, shapes their entire lives and is the most significant hallmark of Jain identity.{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=154-160}}{{sfn|Jindal|1988|p=74-90}}{{sfn|Tähtinen|1976|p=110}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=176-177}} A side effect of this strict discipline is the exercise of [[asceticism]], which is strongly encouraged in Jainism for lay people as well as for monks and nuns.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=187-192}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=199-200}}{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=153-159}} Out of the five types of living beings, a householder is forbidden to kill, or destroy, intentionally, all except the lowest (the one sensed, such as vegetables, herbs, cereals, etc., which are endowed with only the sense of touch).{{sfn|Champat Rai Jain|1917|p=79}}

==Practice==
*For Jains, [[lacto-vegetarianism]] is mandatory. Food is restricted to that originating from plants, since plants have only one sense ('ekindriya') and are the least developed form of life, and dairy products. Food that contains even the smallest particles of the bodies of dead animals or eggs is unacceptable.{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=166-169}}{{sfn|Tähtinen|1976|p=37}} Some Jain scholars and activists support [[veganism]], as the modern commercialised production of dairy products is perceived to involve violence against cows. In ancient times, dairy animals were well cared for and not killed. According to Jain texts, a ''[[Śrāvaka (Jainism)|śrāvaka]]'' (householder) shouldn't consume the four ''maha-vigai'' (the four perversions) - wine, flesh, butter and honey; and the five ''udumbara'' fruits (the five udumbara trees are Gular, Anjeera, Banyan, Peepal, and Pakar, all belonging to the fig class).{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=44}}<ref name=ndtv0417>{{citation |title=Mahavir Jayanti 2017: A beginner's  a guide to Jain food |url=http://m.food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2017-a-beginners-guide-to-jain-food-1679071 |work=[[NDTV]] |date=9 April 2017 }}</ref>
*Jains go out of their way so as not to hurt even small insects and other tiny animals,{{sfn|Jindal|1988|p=89}}{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|p=54}}{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=154-155}}{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|p=180}} because they believe that harm caused by carelessness is as reprehensible as harm caused by deliberate action.<ref>Sutrakrtangasutram 1.8.3</ref><ref>Uttaradhyayanasutra 10</ref><ref>Tattvarthasutra 7.8</ref>{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=161-162}}{{sfn|Granoff|1992|pp=32-35}} Hence they take great pains to make sure that no minuscule animals are injured by the preparation of their meals and in the process of eating and drinking.{{sfn|Sangave|1980|pp=260-261}}{{sfn|Tähtinen|1976|p=109}}
*Traditionally Jains have been prohibited from drinking unfiltered water. In the past, when [[stepwell]]s were used for the water source, the cloth used for filtering was reversed, and some filtered water poured over it to return the organisms to the original body of water. This practice of ''jivani'' or ''bilchavani'' is no longer possible because of the use of pipes for water supply. Modern Jains may also filter tap water in the traditional fashion and a few continue to follow the filtering process even with commercial mineral or bottled drinking water.
*Jains make considerable efforts not to injure plants in everyday life as far as possible. Jains only accept such violence inasmuch as it is indispensable for human survival, and there are special instructions for preventing unnecessary violence against plants.{{sfn|Lodha|1990|pp=137-141}}{{sfn|Tähtinen|1976|p=105}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=106}} Strict Jains don’t eat [[list of root vegetables|root vegetables]] such as potatoes, onions, roots and tubers, because such root vegetables are considered ''ananthkay''.<ref name=ndtv0417/> Ananthkay means one body, but containing infinite lives. A root vegetable such as potato, though from the looks of it is one article, is said to contain infinite lives in it. Also, tiny life forms are injured when the plant is pulled up and because the bulb is seen as a living being, as it is able to sprout.{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=156-157}}{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=167-170}}{{sfn|Sangave|1980|p=260}} Also, consumption of most root vegetables involves uprooting and killing the entire plant, whereas consumption of most terrestrial vegetables doesn't kill the plant (it lives on after plucking the vegetables or it was seasonally supposed to wither away anyway). Green vegetables and fruits contain uncountable, but not infinite, lives. Dry beans, lentils, cereals, nuts and seeds contain a countable number of lives and their consumption results in the least destruction of life. 
* Mushrooms, fungus and yeasts are forbidden because they grow in non-hygienic environments and may harbour other life forms.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}
*Honey is forbidden, as its collection would amount to violence against the bees.<ref>[[Hemacandra]]: ''Yogashastra'' 3.37</ref>{{sfn|Laidlaw|1995|pp=166-167}}{{sfn|Tähtinen|1976|p=109}}
*Jain texts declare that a ''śrāvaka'' (householder) shouldn't cook or eat at night. According to Acharya Amritchandra's [[Purushartha Siddhyupaya]]:
{{quote|And, how can one who eats food without the light of the sun, albeit a lamp may have been lighted, avoid ''hiṃsā'' of minute beings which get into food?|''Puruşārthasiddhyupāya'' (133){{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=86}}}}
*Strict Jains do not consume food that has been stored overnight, as it possesses a higher concentration of micro-organisms (for example, bacteria, yeast etc.) as compared to food prepared and consumed the same day. Hence, they do not consume [[yoghurt]] or [[dhokla]] and [[idli]] batter unless they have been freshly set on the same day.
*During certain days of the month and on important religious days such as [[Paryushana]] and 'Ayambil', strict Jains avoid eating green leafy vegetables along with the usual restrictions on root vegetables. Even with these restrictions, Jains have developed a wide-ranging cuisine. Apart from the regular vegetables, plain yeastless fresh bread, lentils and rice (''dal chawal - roti''), Jains prepare various delicacies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yourvegrecipe.com/jain-recipes-paryushan|title=The Ultimate Guide to Jain Recipes for Paryushan - Your Veg Recipe|website=yourvegrecipe.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-07}}</ref>
* Jains do not consume fermented foods (beer, wine and other alcohols) to avoid killing of a large number of microorganisms associated with the fermenting process.<ref>{{citation |title=Mahavir Jayanti 2015: The importance of a Satvik meal |url=http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2015-the-importance-of-a-satvik-meal-751655 |work=[[NDTV]] |date=2 April 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404075153/http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2015-the-importance-of-a-satvik-meal-751655 |archivedate=4 April 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to ''Puruṣārthasiddhyupāya'':
{{quote|Wine deludes the mind and a deluded person tends to forget piety; the person who forgets piety commits ''hiṃsā'' without hesitation.|''[[Puruşārthasiddhyupāya]]'' (62){{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=45}} }}

==Influence on vegetarian cuisines in India==
The vegetarian cuisines of some regions of the [[Indian subcontinent]] have been strongly influenced by Jainism. These include
* [[Gujarati Jain]] cuisine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2004/06/30/stories/2004063000290400.htm |title=Catering to Jain palate |publisher=The Hindu |date=2004-06-30 |accessdate=2010-05-05}}</ref>
* [[Marwari Jain]] cuisine of Rajasthan
* [[Bundelkhandi Jain]] cuisine of central India
* [[Agrawal Jain]] cuisine of Delhi/UP
* [[Marathi Jain]] cuisine of South Maharashtra
* [[Jain Bunt]] cuisine of Karnataka
* [[Kannada Jains]] cuisine of Karnataka
* [[Tamil Jain]]s cuisine of Northern Districts of Tamil Nadu.

In India, vegetarian food is considered appropriate for everyone for all occasions. This makes vegetarian restaurants quite popular. Many vegetarian restaurants and Mishtanna sweet-shops – for example, the legendary [[Ghantewala]] sweets of [[Delhi]]<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/mp/2002/11/07/stories/2002110700040300.htm |title=A royal treat in Chandni Chowk |work=Hinduonnet.com |date=7 November 2002 }}</ref> and Jamna Mithya in [[Sagar, Madhya Pradesh|Sagar]] – are run by Jains.

Some restaurants in India serve Jain versions of vegetarian dishes that leave out carrots, potatoes, onions and garlic. A few airlines serve Jain vegetarian dishes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.happycow.net/travel/air_travel.html |title=Air Travel Vegetarian Style |work=Happycow.net |date= |accessdate=2010-05-05}}</ref> upon prior request.
Strict Jain cuisine excludes other root vegetables like carrots, beetroot, potatoes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tarladalal.com/ViewContributedRecipe.asp?Id=25 |title=Jain recipes |work=Tarladalal.com }}</ref>

==Historical background==
When [[Mahavira]] revived and reorganized the Jain community in the 6th century BCE, ''ahimsa'' was already an established, strictly observed rule.{{sfn|Goyal|1987|pp=83-85}}{{sfn|Chatterjee|2000|p=14}} [[Parshvanatha]], a [[tirthankara]] whom modern Western historians consider a historical figure,{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=19, 30}}{{sfn|Tähtinen|1976|p=132}} lived in about the 8th century BCE{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=30}}{{sfn|Chatterjee|2000|p=15}} and founded a community to which Mahavira’s parents belonged.<ref>[[Acaranga Sutra]] 2.15</ref>{{sfn|Chatterjee|2000|pp=20-21}} Parshvanatha’s followers vowed to observe ''ahimsa''; this obligation was part of their ''caujjama dhamma'' (Fourfold Restraint).<ref>[[Sthananga Sutra]] 266</ref>{{sfn|Goyal|1987|pp=83-84}}{{sfn|Goyal|1987|p=103}}{{sfn|Tähtinen|1976|p=132}}

In the times of Mahavira and in the following centuries, Jains criticized Buddhists and followers of the [[Historical Vedic religion|Vedic religion]] or Hindus for negligence and inconsistency in the implementation of [[ahimsa]]. In particular, they strongly objected to the Vedic tradition of [[animal sacrifice]] with subsequent meat-eating, and to hunting.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=160}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=234}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=241}}{{sfn|Wiley|2006|p=448}}{{sfn|Granoff|1992|pp=1-43}}{{sfn|Tähtinen|1976|pp=8-9}}

According to the famous Tamil classic, [[Tirukkuṛaḷ]], which is also considered a Jain work by some scholars:
<blockquote>If the world did not purchase and consume meat, no one would slaughter and offer meat for sale. (Kural 256){{sfn|Tiruvaḷḷuvar|2000}}</blockquote>

Some Brahmins—[[Kashmiri Pandit]]s, [[Bengali Brahmins]] and [[Saraswat Brahmin]]s—have traditionally eaten meat (primarily seafood). However, in regions with strong Jain influence such as [[Rajasthan]] and [[Gujarat]], or strong Jain influence in the past such as [[Karnataka]] and [[Tamil Nadu]], Brahmins are strict vegetarians.  Bal Gangadhar Tilak has described Jainism as the originator of ahimsa.  He wrote in a letter:<blockquote>In ancient times, innumerable animals were butchered in sacrifices. Evidence in support of this is found in various poetic compositions such as the Meghaduta. But the credit for the disappearance of this terrible massacre from the Brahminical religion goes to Jainism.<ref>Bombay Samachar, Mumbai:10 Dec, 1904</ref></blockquote>

Some scholars claim that ancient Jain ascetics accepted meat as alms if the animal had not been specifically killed for them.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=177}}{{sfn|Alsdorf|1962|pp=564-570}}{{sfn|Jagdishchandra Jain|1984|p=171}} If this is correct, then they applied the same standard as early Buddhists. Some passages in two of the earliest [[Śvētāmbara]] texts, the ''[[Acaranga Sutra]]'' and the ''Dasaveyaliya'', have been interpreted as regulations for specific types of meat and bones which were considered acceptable alms.<ref>Acaranga Sutra 2.1.10.5-6</ref><ref>Dasaveyaliya 5.1.73 and 5.1.84-86.</ref> This can also be interpreted as references to fruits and seeds. Medieval Jain commentators on these passages interpreted them in the literal sense, but also mentioned the opinion that the offensive words had different meanings, some of which did not refer to animals and hence were compatible with vegetarianism.<ref>Shilanka in his commentary on the ''Acaranga Sutra'' (completed in 872 CE; non-vegetarian interpretation), [[Haribhadra]] in his commentary on the ''Dasaveyaliya'' (8th century CE; both interpretations), Abhayadeva in his commentary on the ''Viyahapannatti'' (11th century CE; both interpretations)</ref>{{sfn|Alsdorf|1962|pp=566-568}}{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|pp=171-172}}{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=177}} Modern Jains, who are strict vegetarians or, to the least, lacto-vegetarians, prefer the latter interpretation of these scholars on this matter.{{sfn|Alsdorf|1962|p=564}}{{sfn|Alsdorf|1962|pp=568-569}}<ref>{{cite wikisource
 | class        = journal
 | first        = Hermann
 | last         = Jacobi
 | chapter      = Jacobi's letter on Acaranga controversy of meat-eating
 | plaintitle   = The Review of Philosophy and Religion
 | editor       = Kapaida, H. R. "Prohibition of Flesh Eating in Jainism"
 | volume       = IV
 | series       = 2
 | year         = 1933
 | origyear     = 1928 
}}</ref> Considering the Jain record of strict vegetarianism from ancient times continuing to the modern age, it is highly unlikely if not impossible that Jain laypersons, let alone Jain monks, would have consumed meat in any form.

