==Reptiles== [[Image:Cnemidophorus-ThreeSpecies.jpg|thumb|Three species of ''[[Aspidoscelis]]''.]] The all-female [[Whiptail lizard]] species ''[[Aspidoscelis neomexicanus]]'' (center), which reproduces via [[parthenogenesis]], is shown flanked by two sexual species having males, ''[[Aspidoscelis inornatus|A. inornatus]]'' (left) and ''[[Aspidoscelis tigris|A. tigris]]'' (right). Research has shown that simulated mating behavior increases fertility for ''Aspidoscelis neomexicanus''. One female lies on top of another, playing the role of the male, the lizard that was on bottom has larger eggs, in most cases. The lizards switch off this role each mating season.<ref>LeVay, (19 September 2007)</ref> <!--- PLEASE NOTE, although most of this list of from one source every item has been referenced. Please only add items with reference or leave a note on the article talk page if unsure. ---> {{div col|colwidth=25em}} *[[Anole]] sp.<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Wood Turtle">Bagemihl (1999), page 657</ref> *[[Bearded dragon]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Lizard"/> *[[Blue-tailed day gecko]] (''Phelsuma cepediana'')<ref name = Budzinski1997>Budzinski, R.-M. (1997) Homosexuelles Verhalten bei Geckos der Gattung Phelsuma. Sauria 19 (3): 33-34</ref> *[[Broad-headed skink]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Common Garter Snake"/> *[[Lizard|Checkered whiptail lizard]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Lizard">Bagemihl (1999), page 657, 658</ref> *[[Lizard|Chihuahuan spotted whiptail lizard]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Lizard"/> *[[Ameiva|Common ameiva]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Lizard"/> *[[Common garter snake]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Common Garter Snake"/> *[[Anole|Cuban green anole]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Wood Turtle"/> *[[Desert grassland whiptail lizard]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Lizard"/> *[[Desert tortoise]]<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Desert Tortoise">Bagemihl (1999), pages 232, 664</ref> *Fence lizard<ref name="Biol. Exuberance: Lizard"/> *[[Plestiodon fasciatus|Five-lin