{{short description|First period of the Paleoproterozoic Era}}
{{Geological period
|timeline=off
|image=
|caption= Map of Siderian
}}
[[File:Banded iron formation Dales Gorge.jpg|thumb|A Siderian banded iron formation in Dales Gorge, [[Western Australia]]]]

The '''Siderian Period''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|s|aɪ|ˈ|d|ɪər|i|ən}}; {{lang-el|σίδηρος|translit=sídēros}}, meaning "iron") is the first [[geologic]] [[geologic period|period]] in the [[Paleoproterozoic]] [[era (geology)|Era]] and lasted from {{Period start|Siderian}} [[annum|Ma]] to {{Period start|Rhyacian}} Ma (million years ago). Instead of being based on [[stratigraphy]], these dates are defined [[Absolute dating|chronometrically]].

The laying down of the [[banded iron formation]]s (BIFs) peaked early in this period. BIFs were formed as anaerobic [[cyanobacteria]] produced waste [[oxygen]] that combined with [[iron]], forming [[magnetite]] (Fe<sub>3</sub>O<sub>4</sub>, an [[iron oxide]]). This process removed iron from the Earth's oceans, presumably turning greenish seas clear. Eventually, with no remaining iron in the oceans to serve as an oxygen sink, the process allowed the buildup of an oxygen-rich [[Earth's atmosphere|atmosphere]]. This second, follow-on event is known as the [[oxygen catastrophe]], which, some geologists believe triggered the [[Huronian glaciation]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Paleoclimates: The First Two Billion Years |first1=James F. |last1=Kasting |first2=Shuehi |last2=Ono |year=2006 |journal=Philosophical Transactions: Biological Sciences |volume=361 |issue=1470 |pages=917–929 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2006.1839 |jstor=20209693|pmc=1868609 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The Paleoproterozoic Snowball Earth: A climate disaster triggered by the evolution of oxygenic photosynthesis |first1=Robert E. |last1=Kopp |first2=Joseph L. |last2=Kirschvink |first3=Isaac A. |last3=Hilburn |first4=Cody Z. |last4=Nash |journal=PNAS |year=2005 |volume=102 |issue=32 |pages=11131–11136 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0504878102|url=http://authors.library.caltech.edu/1015/1/KOPpnas05.pdf }}</ref>

Since the time period from 2420&nbsp;Ma to 2250&nbsp;Ma is well-defined by the lower edge of iron-deposition layers, an alternative period named the '''Oxygenian''', based on stratigraphy instead of chronometry, was suggested in 2012 by Gradstein ''et al.'' in a geological timescale review <ref name="Gradstein_et_al_2012">{{cite book |title=The Geologic Time Scale 2012 |publisher=Elsevier |editor1-last=Gradstein |editor1-first=F. M. |display-editors=etal |year=2012 |volume=1 |pages=361–365 |isbn=978-0-44-459390-0}}</ref> but, {{As of|2017|02|lc=y}}, this has not yet been officially adopted by the [[IUGS]].

